e the new path at all.\n- Backward compatibility for any API/contract/serialization you touched.\n\nQuick gut-check: **what work is no longer happening, and is it always safe to skip?** If you can answer that crisply, you\u0027re probably fine. If the honest answer is \"not sure why it\u0027s faster,\" that\u0027s the thing to chase down before shipping."}
{"task":"green","arm":"concise","run":2,"output_tokens":766,"is_error":false,"answer":"Green tests and a latency win are exactly when a change is easiest to over-trust. Things to check before you ship it:\n\n**The tests themselves**\n- 47 passing means little if none of them exercise the code path you changed. Check coverage on the actual diff, not the whole suite.\n- Did you *add* tests for the new behavior, or just not break old ones? A 30% latency drop usually means you changed *how* something works ‚Äî there should be a test asserting the new semantics.\n- Are any of these tests asserting on the old slow path in a way that would still pass against a subtly wrong fast path?\n\n**Where the 30% came from** ‚Äî this is the real risk. Speedups are rarely free. Identify the mechanism:\n- **Caching / memoization?** Watch for staleness, cache-key collisions, and unbounded memory growth. Correct on the first call, wrong on the second.\n- **Removed or loosened locking / added concurrency?** Tests usually run single-threaded and won\u0027t surface races. This is the classic \"green in CI, corrupt in prod.\"\n- **Dropped a round trip, batched, or added parallelism?** Check error handling ‚Äî partial failures, ordering guarantees, and timeout behavior often change.\n- **Weaker consistency** (async where it was sync, eventual where it was strong)? Correctness now depends on timing.\n- **Skipped validation / early return / short-circuit?** Fast because it does less ‚Äî make sure \"less\" isn\u0027t \"less correct.\"\n\n**Where you measured**\n- Warm cache, hot JIT, local box, small dataset? Measure on realistic data volume and cold state. p50 dropping 30% while p99 gets worse is a real and common outcome ‚Äî look at tail latency, not just the mean.\n- Was the workload representative, or a microbenchmark of the happy path?\n\n**Edge cases that green tests miss**\n- Empty inputs, large inputs, error paths, concurrent access, resource cleanup (connections/handles/goroutines), and memory under sustained load.\n\nConcretely: tell me *what* the change was and *why* it\u0027s faster. The mechanism dictates the risk ‚Äî \"faster and all green\" with no explanation is the pattern that pages you at 3am. If you can name the mechanism and point to a test that pins the new behavior (including one failure/edge path), you\u0027re in good shape."}
