{"task":"green","arm":"baseline","run":3,"output_tokens":998,"is_error":false,"answer":"Passing tests and lower latency are necessary but not sufficient signals. Here\u0027s what I\u0027d check before trusting that result:\n\n## The tests\n- **Do the 47 tests actually cover the changed code?** Green tests only mean something if they exercise your change. Check coverage on the specific lines/branches you touched. A pre-existing suite often has blind spots exactly where new logic lives.\n- **Did you add tests for the new behavior/edge cases?** If the change enabled a new path and all 47 tests predate it, they can\u0027t have caught a regression in it.\n- **Are any of them flaky or trivially passing?** Confirm they\u0027d actually fail if the logic were wrong (mutation-test mentally, or break something on purpose and watch it go red).\n\n## The 30% latency drop ‚Äî treat as a claim to verify, not a win\nA speedup this clean is as often a bug as an optimization. Ask *why* it got faster:\n- **Are you doing less work, or less correct work?** Common culprits: caching something that shouldn\u0027t be cached (stale reads), skipping validation, dropping a `fsync`/flush, short-circuiting before a side effect, or returning before an async task completes.\n- **Weakened consistency/durability?** Removing a lock, a barrier, or an `await` speeds things up and introduces race conditions or lost writes that no unit test will catch.\n- **Where was it measured?** Warm cache vs cold, single request vs under concurrency, local vs prod-like data volumes. A 30% p50 win can hide a p99 regression. Look at tail latency, not just the mean.\n- **Load and concurrency:** does the gain hold under realistic parallel traffic, or did you just move contention somewhere it\u0027ll bite later?\n\n## Beyond correctness and speed\n- **Resource trade-offs:** faster often means more memory, more connections, bigger cache, or more CPU burst. Check you didn\u0027t trade latency for a memory/FD/thread-pool leak.\n- **Error paths:** did the change alter behavior on timeouts, retries, partial failures? Those rarely have test coverage.\n- **Backward compatibility:** API shape, serialization format, DB migration, config defaults.\n- **Observability:** make sure logs/metrics/traces still fire ‚Äî a common \"speedup\" is accidentally disabling instrumentation.\n\n## Concrete next steps\n1. Run coverage scoped to the diff; add tests for anything uncovered.\n2. Load/soak test and look at **p95/p99**, not the average, under concurrent traffic.\n3. Write down the *mechanism* for the speedup in one sentence. If you can\u0027t explain why it\u0027s faster, you don\u0027t yet know whether it\u0027s correct.\n4. Diff behavior on failure/edge inputs, not just the happy path.\n\nBottom line: \"tests pass + faster\" is a great start, but the speedup is the part that most deserves suspicion ‚Äî verify it came from doing less *unnecessary* work, not from skipping *necessary* work."}
