ence? If the mechanism is clear and benign (better algorithm, fewer round-trips, an index), you\u0027re probably fine. If \"not sure, it just is\" ‚Äî that\u0027s the one to dig into."}
{"task":"green","arm":"capisce","run":3,"output_tokens":1572,"is_error":false,"answer":"Solid result ‚Äî but \"all green + faster\" is exactly the combination that hides regressions, because the speed usually came from *doing less*, and the tests only prove the paths they cover. Things to check before you trust it:\n\n**What did the latency actually cost you?**\n- If you removed or shortened work ‚Äî validation, a lock, a sync barrier, retries, a defensive copy ‚Äî the 30% is that work not happening. Make sure it wasn\u0027t load-bearing (correctness, safety under concurrency, backpressure).\n- If you added caching, the win comes with an invalidation problem: staleness, cache stampede on cold start, and correctness when the underlying data changes.\n- If you raised concurrency/parallelism, you traded latency for resource pressure ‚Äî connection pool exhaustion, memory, thread starvation under real load.\n\n**Is the measurement real?**\n- **Mean vs tail.** 30% off the average can coexist with *worse* p95/p99. Look at the tail, not just the headline number.\n- **Cold vs warm.** Was the benchmark warm-cache, small dataset, single client? Prod is cold caches, big data, concurrent load. Re-measure at prod-like scale.\n- **Variance.** One run isn\u0027t a trend. Confirm it\u0027s stable across repeated runs.\n\n**Do the tests actually cover the change?**\n- 47 passing means 47 assertions held ‚Äî not that the changed lines are exercised. Check line/branch coverage on the diff specifically.\n- Unit tests are almost always the happy path. The risk lives in error paths, concurrent access, and edge inputs. Add a test that would *fail* if your optimization broke correctness ‚Äî if you can\u0027t write one, you don\u0027t yet know what you traded.\n\n**Second-order stuff:**\n- Memory/CPU footprint ‚Äî did you buy speed with a bigger resident set that bites later (GC pressure, OOM)?\n- Behavior under failure ‚Äî timeouts, partial results, retries after the change.\n\nQuickest sanity move: write one test that pins the *correctness invariant* the optimization touches, and run the benchmark cold at realistic scale while watching p99. If both hold, ship it."}
